course_aims:
This course aims to provide an introduction to business analysis, financial statement analysis and valuation using financial statement data. You will leave this course with a company business analysis and valuation for a selected listed Australian company . This valuation includes a summary of your strategy, financial, forecasting and valuation analyses and provides a recommendation for investors in relation to the shares of the company selected for analysis.

Valuation is a highly speculative undertaking. This course introduces a systematic, state of the art approach to valuation that reduces the input of pure speculation by emphasising the importance of knowing the business, the business environment, and the appropriate data and valuation model to use for the type of company you are trying to value. Some students are impatient with the upfront, fundamental 'business and financial' analysis requirements, but beware the valuation failures of the financial analyst who does not thoroughly understand the company's fundamentals! Students who commit to the course, set individual and Team tasks, and attend classes will gain knowledge and skills that can be used in practice.

The main aims of this course are to help students:

Understand the basic techniques of financial analysis and business valuation using a structured approach;

Appreciate the importance to valuation of the linkages between industry and strategy, financial statement information, forecasting, capital market participants, and the estimation of the intrinsic value of a common share;

Understand how financial statements are used in the valuation process;

Understand how to use different valuation models and their benefits and limitations;

Develop the skills to prepare a valuation and stock recommendation and justify it in terms of the business context.
